  {
    "type": "EXPOSITORY (ENGLISH BIBLE)",
    "name": "Ellicott's Commentary for English Readers",
    "elements": [
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "(26) ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "bld",
        "text": "He hoped also that money should have been given him of Paul.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "—The Greek gives “hoping also,” as continuing the previous verse, and so places the fact in more immediate connection with the procurator’s conduct. This greed of gain in the very act of administering justice was the root-evil of the weak and wicked character. He had caught at the word “alms” in ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Acts 24:17",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ". St. Paul, then, was not without resources. He had money himself, or he had wealthy friends; could not something be got out of one or both for the freedom which the prisoner would naturally desire?",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "p",
        "class": "",
        "text": "He sent for him the oftener, and communed with him.—It is not difficult to represent to ourselves the character of these interviews, the suggestive hints—half-promises and half-threats—of the procurator, the steadfast refusal of the prisoner to purchase the freedom which he claimed as a right, his fruitless attempts to bring about a change for the better in his judge’s character.",
        "children": [
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "bld",
            "text": "He sent for him the oftener, and communed with him.",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "",
            "text": "—It is not difficult to represent to ourselves the character of these interviews, the suggestive hints—half-promises and half-threats—of the procurator, the steadfast refusal of the prisoner to purchase the freedom which he claimed as a right, his fruitless attempts to bring about a change for the better in his judge’s character.",
            "children": []
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "element": "p",
        "class": "",
        "text": "",
        "children": []
